Plant material innovation at Land Grant Universities

Intellectural property protections and matieral licensing, 1980-2020

Liza Wood, Adam Vera, Victoria Fletcher

2022-10-19

This page summarizes plant breeding activities at US Land Grant Universities (LGUs) and the subsequent trends in technology transfer between universities and companies. Data for these summaries are combined across four sources:
1. PVP database
2. USPTO database
3. Licensing metadata from 25 LGUs, collected via FOIA requests
4. Company data collected from the D&B Hoovers database

How have LGUs been protecting their plant material?

The PVP and USPTO databases were scraped and automated text matching was used to identify applications by the 50 1862 LGUs. For PVPs, this meant looking for applications with Universities as Applicants, and for USPTO, this meant looking for LGUs as Assignees, as well as Agricultural Research Centers and State applications that were observed in the licensing agreements (see below).

Between 1980-2020 2350 applications have been submitted by LGUs, 1851 as PVP and 806 as USPTO (739 as plant patents and 67 as utility patents). There have a steady increase in both IP types over time:

Technology transfer: What happens to these varieties?

Universities license the plant material they develop some of it protected, others not to third parties to commercialize and/or continue to innovation. I collected records of licensing data between 2000-2020 for 25 LGUs to summarize what material is being licenses, and to whom.

Preliminary look at these data include the following features:

  • 7610 licensing agreements across 25 Land Grant Universities between 2000-2020
  • Agreements are with 1098 companies and 134 other entities (organizations, universities, individuals, etc.)
  • 1865 unique plant varieties and/or breeding lines are licensed, but only [X, X%] are protected by PVPs and patents. In many other cases the licensed materials are breeding lines/unfinished varieties (X%), or ?
